## TOP / LIMIT

Limits how many rows come back.

> SQL Server uses `TOP`. MySQL/PostgreSQL use `LIMIT`. Same idea, different keyword.

**Example**
```sql
SELECT TOP 3 *
FROM customers;
```

```
customers (7 rows)        TOP 3 result
в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ                   в”Ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”җ
в”Ӯ row1в”Ӯ в—„в”Җв”Җ keep          в”Ӯ row1в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ row2в”Ӯ в—„в”Җв”Җ keep          в”Ӯ row2в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ row3в”Ӯ в—„в”Җв”Җ keep          в”Ӯ row3в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ row4в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ... в”Ӯ
в””в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҳ
```

> **Warning:** `TOP`/`LIMIT` without `ORDER BY` gives you *some* rows, not the "best" ones. Always sort first:
> ```sql
> SELECT TOP 3 * FROM customers ORDER BY score DESC;
> ```

